Predict The Bay Area’s Home Prices¶

About Data

  • The dataset for this project contains information about real estate properties in San Francisco, including their addresses, sale prices, number of bedrooms and bathrooms, finished square footage, year built, and other features
  • This dataset was based on the homes sold between January 2013 and December 2015 and it was sourced from Bay Area Home Sales Database and Zillow
  • Dataset: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jasondata918/dataset/main/final_data.csv

Data Cleaning and Preprocessing

  • Removing unnecessary columns and converting it to int datatype
  • One-Hot Encoding: Encoding categorical columns

Exploratory Data Analysis

  • Creating a histogram of the dataset
  • Creating a scatter plot
  • Analyzing correlations

Model Training and Evaluation

  • Splitting the dataset into training and testing sets
  • Training Linear Regression model, Ridge model and Lasso model on the training set
  • Making predictions on the testing set and evaluating the model's performance by RMSE

Conclusion

  • Summary of the project and its findings

2. Neighborhood Analysis¶

The code groups the dataset by neighborhood and calculates the frequency and average price per square foot for each neighborhood. It then creates a new variable called "group" based on these values and merges it with the original dataset. The goal of this project could be to further explore the relationship between neighborhood and house prices and to identify which neighborhoods are the most expensive or affordable.

In [17]:
sf['neighborhood'].nunique()
Out[17]:
71

cluster the neighborhood into three groups

  1. low price
  2. high price low frequency
  3. high price high frequency
In [18]:
freq = sf.groupby('neighborhood').count() ['address']
mean = sf.groupby('neighborhood').mean()['price_per_sqft']
cluster = pd.concat([freq, mean], axis = 1)
cluster['neighborhood'] = cluster.index 
cluster.columns = ['freq', 'price_per_sqft', 'neighborhood']
cluster.describe()

In [19]:
def get_group(x) :
  if x['price_per_sqft'] <756:
    return 'low_price'
  elif (x['price_per_sqft'] >=756) & (x['freq'] <123) :
    return 'high_price_low_freq'
  else:
    return 'high_price_high_freq'
In [20]:
group = cluster.apply(get_group, axis = 1).reset_index()
In [21]:
sf = sf.merge(group)
sf.rename({0:'group'}, axis = 1, inplace = True)

3. Building a predictive model¶

The code builds a linear regression model to predict the last sold price of a property based on various features such as bathrooms, bedrooms, finished square feet, total rooms, year built, and neighborhood. The goal of building a predictive model is to accurately predict the last sold price of a property based on its features.

Model Training and Evaluation

  • Splitting the dataset into training and testing sets
  • Training a linear regression model on the training set

In [54]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(12,8))
alphas = [0.01, 0.5, 10, 100]

for alpha, ax in zip(alphas, axes.flatten()):
    ridge = Ridge(alpha=alpha)
    ridge.fit(X_train, y_train)

    coef = pd.Series(ridge.coef_, index=X_train.columns).sort_values()
    sns.barplot(x=coef.index, y=coef.values, ax=ax, palette='coolwarm')
    ax.set_xticklabels(coef.index, rotation=90)
    ax.set_xlabel('Features')
    ax.set_ylabel('Coefficient')
    ax.set_title('Ridge Regression Coefficients lambda ={}'.format(alpha))

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

4. Model Evaluation¶

The code evaluates the performance of the linear regression model using root mean squared error (RMSE). Model evaluation is an essential step in the data analysis process as it allows for the identification of potential issues with the model, such as overfitting or underfitting.

In [33]:
import numpy as np
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

5. Conclusion¶

Overall, the goal of this project is to use data analysis techniques to gain insights into the housing market in San Francisco and build a predictive model that can accurately predict the last sold price of a property.

  • Based on the RMSE values provided, it seems that the Ridge model performs slightly better than both the Linear Regression and Lasso models. However, the difference in the RMSE values is not very large, so further analysis may be necessary to determine which model is truly the best fit for the data.
